name: 3-chloro-4-methoxybenzonitrile
Reason: Starting with the basic unit (benzene), which has a melting point of around 5.5 degrees Celsius, we take into account the substituents on the benzene ring. Each substituent can increase or decrease the melting point depending on its nature (electron-withdrawing or electron-donating) and its effect on the crystal packing. The chloro group is electron-withdrawing and has a polarizing effect, which can lead to stronger intermolecular forces through dipole-dipole interactions and thus increase the melting point, typically by about +20 degrees due to chlorine's size and electronegativity. The methoxy group is an electron-donating group and usually lowers the melting point due to steric hindrance, which can disrupt crystal packing, but in this case it may also engage in dipole-dipole interactions due to the oxygen atom, so it might give a slight increase of +5 degrees. The nitrile group is a strong electron-withdrawing group and typically raises the melting point considerably (+50 degrees) due to its ability to engage in strong dipolar interactions and possibly even hydrogen bonding. Combining these effects, we get a predicted increase of 75 degrees over the base melting point of benzene.
